      "title": "Setup: AIG has TWO outputs (t and g); we focus on t, cut = {p, q, e, h}",
      "narrative": "An MFFC w.r.t. a cut is the set of internal ANDs that would die if the target were replaced — but only counting nodes <em>above</em> the cut. Cut leaves and everything below them must stay alive.<br><br>This AIG has two outputs: <strong>t</strong> (target) and <strong>g</strong> (separate). They share PI <code>a</code> but have disjoint internal cones. <em>g and its branch should NOT end up in t's MFFC.</em><br><br>Cut for t: <code>{p, q, e, h}</code> — two internal ANDs and two PIs. Each cut leaf has fanout <code>[1]</code> INTO t's cone, so without protection deref would walk past them.<br><br>Every node shows its current <code>fanouts</code> count next to it as <code>[N]</code>.",
      "highlights": {
        "node-t": ["considering"]
      },
      "panes": [
        {
          "type": "kv",
          "title": "Circuit",
          "entries": {
            "p": "a · b   <em>(cut leaf — internal AND, fanout 1)</em>",
            "q": "c · d   <em>(cut leaf — internal AND, fanout 1)</em>",
            "m": "p · q",
            "n": "e · h",
            "t": "m · n   <em>(target)</em>",
            "g": "a · y   <em>(separate output — outside t's cone)</em>"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "title": "What the answer should be",
          "body": "MFFC of t = <code>{ t, m, n }</code>. p, q, e, h survive (cut leaves). g, y, PO_g and PI a's fanout to g are <strong>untouched</strong> — they're not in t's cone at all."
        }
